text: 1927 King George V and Queen Mary of Teck World population reaches 2,000,000,000.  January 1   The Cristero War erupts in Mexico, when Catholic rebels attack the government, which had placed heavy restrictions on the Catholic Church.  The British Broadcasting Company becomes the British Broadcasting Corporation, when it is granted a Royal Charter of incorporation. John Reith becomes the first Director-General.  January 7   The first transatlantic telephone call is made via radio from New York City to London.  The Harlem Globetrotters play their first ever road game in Hinckley, Illinois. January 10 â€“ Fritz Lang's futuristic film Metropolis is released in Germany.  January 11 â€“ Louis B. Mayer, head of film studio Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer (MGM), announces the creation of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, at a banquet in Los Angeles, California.  January 15 â€“ Teddy Wakelam gives the first sports commentary on BBC Radio.  February 19   A general strike in Shanghai protests the presence of British troops.  In the United States, the silent romantic comedy film It starring Clara Bow, is released, popularising the concept of the "It girl".  February 23 â€“ The U.S. Federal Radio Commission (later renamed the Federal Communications Commission) begins to regulate the use of radio frequencies.  March 4 â€“ A diamond rush in South Africa includes trained athletes, who have been hired by major companies to stake claims.  March 6 â€“ In Britain, 1,000 people a week die from an influenza epidemic. March 11   In New York City, the Roxy Theatre is opened by Samuel Roxy Rothafel.  The first armored car robbery is committed by the Flatheads Gang, near Pittsburgh.  March 14 â€“ Pan American World Airways is founded by Juan T. Trippe.  April 1 â€“ The U.S. Bureau of Prohibition is founded (under the Department of the Treasury). April 7 â€“ Bell Telephone Co. transmits an image of Herbert Hoover (then the Secretary of Commerce), which becomes the first successful long distance demonstration of television. April 12   The Royal and Parliamentary Titles Act 1927 renames the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland as the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland. The change acknowledges that the Irish Free State is no longer part of the Kingdom. April 14 â€“ The first Volvo automobile rolls off the production line in Gothenburg, Sweden. April 22â€“May 5 â€“ The Great Mississippi Flood of 1927 strikes 700,000 people, in the greatest natural disaster in American history through this time.  May â€“ Philo Farnsworth of the United States transmits his first experimental electronic television motion pictures, as opposed to the electromechanical TV systems that others have used before. May 11 â€“ The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, the "Academy" in "Academy Awards", is founded.  May 12 â€“ British police officers raid the office of the Soviet trade delegation in London.  May 13 â€“ King George V proclaims the change of his title, from King of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland to King of Great Britain and Northern Ireland. May 20â€“21â€“ Charles Lindbergh makes the first solo, nonstop transatlantic airplane flight, from New York City to Paris, France, in his single-engined aircraft, the Spirit of St. Louis. May 23 â€“ Nearly 600 members of the American Institute of Electrical Engineers and the Institute of Radio Engineers view a live demonstration of television at the Bell Telephone Building in New York City, just over a year after John Logie Baird of Scotland had first demonstrated an electromechanical television system to the members of the Royal Society in London.  May 24 â€“ The United Kingdom cuts its diplomatic relations with the Soviet Union, due to revelations of espionage and underground agitation.  June 4â€“6 â€“ Clarence Chamberlin and Charles Albert Levine take off from Roosevelt Field, New York, and fly to Eisleben, Germany, in the Wright-Bellanca WB-2 Columbia aircraft Miss Columbia, two weeks after Charles Lindbergh's historic solo flight. June 13   LÃ©on Daudet, the leader of the French monarchists, is arrested in France.  A ticker tape parade is held for aviator Charles Lindbergh, down Fifth Avenue in New York City.  July 1 â€“ The Food, Drug, and Insecticide Administration (FDIA) is established as a United States federal agency.  July 10 â€“ Kevin O'Higgins, Vice-President of the Executive Council of the Irish Free State and Minister for Justice, is assassinated by the anti-Treaty Irish Republican Army in Dublin.  August 2   U.S. President Calvin Coolidge announces, "I do not choose to run for president in 1928." August 10 â€“ The Mount Rushmore Park is rededicated in the United States. President Calvin Coolidge promises national funding for the proposed carving of the presidential figures.  Autumn 1927 - Setting EVENTS DURING MOVIE September 7   The University of Minas Gerais is founded in Brazil.  The first fully electronic television system is achieved by Philo Farnsworth. September 18 â€“ The Columbia Phonographic Broadcasting System (later known as CBS) is formed, and goes on the air with 47 radio stations.  September 25 â€“ A treaty signed by the League of Nations Slavery Commission abolishes all types of slavery.  October 4 â€“ Carving of the sculptures at Mount Rushmore, South Dakota begins.  October 6 â€“ The Jazz Singer, starring Al Jolson, premieres at the Warner Theater in New York City. Although not the first sound film, and containing very little recorded speech, it is the first to become a box-office hit, popularizing "talkies" (although silent films continue to be made for some time).[4] October 18 â€“ The first flight of Pan American Airways takes off from Key West, Florida, bound for Havana, Cuba.  November 12 - The Holland Tunnel opens to traffic, as the first vehicular tunnel under the Hudson River, linking New Jersey with New York City.  December 2 â€“ Following 19 years of Ford Model T production, the Ford Motor Company unveils the Ford Model A as its new automobile in the United States.  December 3 â€“ Putting Pants on Philip, the first Laurel and Hardy film, is released. December 14 â€“ Iraq gains independence from the United Kingdom.

text: Just for the record, given this may be fiction, but based on historical fact. In the late 20's there was no KING AND QUEEN. In fact, you  can not have a king AND queen serving simultaneously as the British sovereign.  The title of King or Queen, is simply a gender identification of the sovereign, and there can only be ONE sovereign. The sovereign, if a king, may appoint a queen consort, but can not be referred to as queen. During this supposed time period the sovereign was George V, who was married to Mary of Teck, his Queen consort. A little surprised a British television company would make this mistake, as local knowledge should know better. Certainly not like the US tabloids who every few weeks proclaim William and Kate to soon become the next King and Queen of England.

text: Julian Fellowes once wrote a wonderful script for a film, "Gosford Park," about fin de siÃ¨cle life in one of England's great manors. One of the things most to be admired about the film was it's glimpse of a dying class system and interactions between masters and servants, with the little lordlings clearly regarding their servants as automatons with no more thoughts and feelings than the bric-a-brac. How astonishing, and not a little depressing, that only a few years later Fellowes concocted this treacly fantasy about inbred rich gits, implausibly empathetic to the feelings and needs of their servants.

text: it  is SO NICE to know that the cast (main family, servants, et al) all turned up for this movie. and there were no stories about one person demanding more money, or bigger trailers, etc.  So nice that they did not have to say that any one had moved away or had pressing business , to explain a character's absence. they were ALL THERE (except that one cousin girl who came after Cybil died). So nice to see that no one thought they were above the movie now, nor that they wanted to not be stereotyped.  These people appreciate their fans, and i am grateful. i will now make an effort to see other things they may be in, to give support, because of this. i am SO tired of loving a character then they insist on more money to come back, or want their character to be killed off because they are tired of playing them. etc etc.  BRAVO to this entire cast!!! and the writers and Julian Fellowes.  this was well done, left us happy, and great to see ALL our beloved cast back in all their glory, and for some, evn MORE glory!!!

text: The Downton movie is just astoundingly dumb from start to finish.  The main storyline has the Downton servants - all of them - agreeing to usurp the Royal household servants in order to cook and serve dinner for the visiting royals.  That overworked, underpaid servants would want to do such a thing rather than more-or-less have the day off makes zero sense, especially given that they'd likely be fired for doing so, were they found out.  And it's not remotely believable that they get away with it.  Julian Fellows has come up with some staggeringly lame and far-fetched plots in the course of the Downton series, but the movie beats them all.

text: The success of the series in the UK was obvious. At the rest of the world? Dont misunderstood me, I loved the series and the movie here is pretty good. But here is a crazy explanation for the worldwide success of the series. Remember back in the day when british "royals" were exploring Africa, Asia, etc to observe and understand "what are they?" (I mean the natives and the animals). Here is the same, the rest of the world watched it to understand "what are they", those stiff people that never worked in their lives (up floors) and the modern day slaves (basement). Am I wrong? The acting and the art of the series and the film are over the top. And that also explains why STILL around us humanoids buy Jags, Rolls, Astons, etc. Its the heritage, the royalty, the "name". text: I absolutely loved the series and the movie now. I own the complete set now. I must say that my favorite person is Maggie Smith who plays Violet. She has me in stitches of laughter with her wit and dry humor. When she was telling Mary that she is dying I burst into tears. This series has me completely transfixed and wanting more. Since acquiring the complete set and movie now I am so happy. It makes me homesick for England and missing certain things and of course that northern accent from some of the actors. I grew up in Manchester. Bravo to the writers of this amazing look at life in England during the early 1900s.
